<h1>I will set a “quit date”</h1>
<h3>SET A QUIT DATE</h3>
<p>Schedule a date to quit! Set aside time, energy, and attention to quitting smoking. Mark it on your calendar.</p>
<p>My Quit date is: </p>
<h3>Prepare for the Quit Date</h3>
<ol>
	<li>Ask your physician about nicotine patch or gum to reduce cravings for cigarettes.</li>
	<li>Have your teeth cleaned. Ask your dentist to review how to clean teeth and gums.</li>
	<li>Tell a friend or family member your plan and ask for support.</li>
	<li>Declare your house a NO SMOKING area. Buy a nice NO SMOKING sign and put it near your front door.</li>
	<li>Make sure you have no cigarettes anywhere (wet them before throwing them away so you won’t take them out of the garbage).</li>
	<li>Throw away all your ashtrays.</li>
</ol>
<h3>ON QUIT DAY</h3>
<p>Quit! Go for it.</p>
<p>
Keep handy your list of healthy alternatives to smoking. This list will help you change your smoking patterns.  Be good to yourself today.
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Change your morning routine. Have breakfast, but don’t sit in the same place at the kitchen table.</li>
	<li>Stay busy.</li>
	<li>Carry some substitutes, like gum, cinnamon sticks, or cinnamon toothpicks.</li>
	<li>Tell those around you that you have quit smoking.</li>
	<li>Promise yourself a reward for getting through the day without smoking (like going to a movie, having a favorite meal, or feeling proud).</li>
	<li>Brush your teeth and use mouth rinse.</li>
	<li>Wear a rubber band on your wrist. Snap it whenever you get the urge to smoke.</li>
	<li>Call or walk with a friend.</li>
</ul>
<h3><em>Cigarette substitutes</em></h3>
<p>Sugarless chewing gum <br>
Carrot sticks, celery, and other crunchy vegetables <br>
Toothpicks <br>
A jigsaw puzzle, magazine, or good book <br>
Drawing, knitting, and sewing <br>
</p>

